</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 At a high point of land in Grant Park with a view of the entire Ventura 
coastline, Jo Ellen Lay and her husband, Gary, planted trees. 
</P>
<P>
 The couple have volunteered to care for the picnic site where they've planted 
25 trees, each one in memory of a deceased relative. 
</P>
<P>
 "When we planted the first trees, we came out here with all the family -- our 
son and daughters and five grandchildren -- and dropped notes into the ground 
in memory of their great-grandmother who had died," Jo Ellen Lay said. 
</P>
<P>
 Since planting those trees in April, the Lays have carried water twice a week 
to the saplings. Thursday, they planted 22 more trees and plan on carrying 
water up to the site until the young pines can survive on their own. The Lays 
said they hope that when the trees are big enough to provide shade, the city 
will build benches nearby. 
</P>
<P>
 "What better way to remember a loved one," Lay said. "It would be wonderful if 
other people could take the idea. The park needs the volunteers, and the trees 
would make the world a nicer place." SCOTT HADLY 
